hint: A hierarchical decomposition of project scope into deliverables and work packages (WBS).
The longest sequence of dependent activities that determines the shortest possible project duration.
Schedule flexibility: how long an activity can slip without delaying the project finish date.
A significant point or event in a project, often used for tracking progress.
A unique product, result, or service that must be produced to complete a process, phase, or project.
A document that formally authorizes the project and gives the PM authority to apply resources.
A justification for the project, including expected benefits and costs.
A plan that describes how and when project benefits will be delivered and measured.
Approved scope statement, WBS, and WBS dictionary used as the basis for comparison.
The approved version of the schedule model used as a basis for comparison.
The approved version of the time-phased project budget used as a basis for comparison.
A record of assumptions and constraints throughout the project.
A register of issues, owners, and resolution status.
A document listing identified risks, responses, owners, and current status.
A document with details about stakeholders: interests, influence, and engagement needs.
Defines what information is shared, to whom, when, and how.
Describes how resources are acquired, managed, and released.
Describes quality standards, how they will be met, and how quality will be measured.
Describes how procurements will be managed, including contract types and roles.
A formally chartered group responsible for approving or rejecting change requests (CCB).
Reviewing change requests, approving changes, and managing baselines.
A formal proposal to modify any document, deliverable, or baseline.
Ensures project artifacts are consistently defined, controlled, and traceable.
A method integrating scope, schedule, and cost to measure performance (EVM).
EV/AC — efficiency of cost utilization (CPI).
EV/PV — efficiency of schedule performance (SPI).
Expected total cost of the project at completion (EAC).
Expected cost to finish all remaining project work (ETC).
How the project is executed, monitored, controlled, and closed.
Selecting and adjusting processes to fit the project context while meeting objectives.
Knowledge gained during the project to improve future performance.
A session to inspect how the team worked and decide improvements (Agile).
A short daily coordination meeting to surface progress and blockers.
A timeboxed iteration in Scrum used to create a usable increment.
An ordered list of work needed to improve the product (Scrum).
Selected Product Backlog items plus a plan to deliver them in the sprint.
Accountable for maximizing product value and managing the Product Backlog (Scrum).
Facilitates Scrum, removes impediments, and coaches the team (Scrum).
A usable, potentially releasable product slice created each sprint.
Shared understanding of what it means for work to be complete and of acceptable quality.
A feature description from an end user perspective, often 'As a… I want… so that…'.
Conditions that must be met for a work item to be accepted.
Amount of work a team completes in a sprint, often measured in story points.
Shows remaining work over time in a sprint or release.
A method focusing on flow, visualizing work, and limiting work in progress (WIP).
A cap on items in progress to improve flow.
Time from request to delivery for a work item.
Time from work start to work finish for a work item.
The smallest product that delivers value and enables learning (MVP).
The implied cost of rework from choosing an easy solution now over a better one.
A structured approach to find underlying causes rather than symptoms.
Responsibility assignment matrix: Responsible, Accountable, Consulted, Informed.
An interface that enables software systems to communicate (Application Programming Interface).
An architecture where small services are independently deployable and loosely coupled.
Continuous Integration/Continuous Delivery: automating build, test, and deployment.
Practices combining development and operations to deliver software faster and more reliably.
Managing infrastructure with versioned code (IaC).
A platform to orchestrate containerized applications.
A platform for building and running applications in containers.
Understanding system state via logs, metrics, and traces.
Verifying identity (who you are).
Granting permissions (what you can do).
Protecting data by transforming it into a secure format.
Handling unplanned interruptions and restoring service.
Finding root causes and preventing incident recurrence.
A blameless review to learn from incidents and improve systems.
